SMALL TALK / GREETING HANDLER / GENERAL QUERIES (must be implemented)
The bot must politely handle general conversational queries before running BM25 search:
- Instead user give the first message the bot should greet the user with text 
- Greetings: Hi, Hello, Hai, Hey, Good morning, Good afternoon, Good evening, etc.
- Thanks: Thank you, Thanks, Thank you so much, thanks,...etc 
- Other common: How are you?, Bye, Good bye, See you
- Time-based responses using the user’s system time (new Date().getHours()):
  - 00:00–11:59 → “Good morning!”
  - 12:00–16:59 → “Good afternoon!”
  - 17:00–23:59 → “Good evening!”
- Responses must be friendly, short, and natural (e.g. “Hi there! How can I help you” or “Good evening! What process would you like to know about?”).
- After a greeting response, the conversation memory still continues normally for follow-up questions.

EXACT ALGORITHMS TO IMPLEMENT (use exactly these):

1. DOCX Parsing & Semantic Chunking Algorithm (State-Machine + Rich Parser)
   Zip + ElementTree → detect headings → extract text + hyperlinks + tables + images (save to images/ folder). Always full rebuild.

2. BM25 Pre-Computation Algorithm 
   Global df, avgDL, N + per-chunk tf_dict, doc_length, keywords.

3. BM25 Scoring Algorithm (JavaScript)  
   Exact Okapi BM25 (k₁=1.2, b=0.75) + title/keyword boost + Bag-of-Words pre-filter. Normalize to percentage.

4. Conversation Memory Algorithm  
   Array of messages → augmented query with last 3 turns.

5. Scalability & File Splitting 
   Split into knowledge_N.js (max 800–1000 chunks each) + generate manifest.json with timestamp.

6. Small Talk / Greeting Handler Algorithm  
   In JS: before BM25 search, check query against a small hardcoded list of greetings with different synonyms. If matched, generate time-based friendly reply using new Date().getHours() and return immediately (do not run BM25). Still save the greeting in conversation history.

7. Rich Rendering + Production Features 
   Sanitize content, show loading spinner, display timestamp, handle “more” requests, fallback message if score too low.

